{{Infobox building | name = La Borsa | image = La Borsa, Valletta.jpeg | image_caption = View of La Borsa | coordinates = {{coord|35|53|57.76|N|14|30|52.46|E|display=inline}} | alternate_names = Exchange Buildings | architectural_style = [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] and [[Rococo#Architecture|rococo]] | location = [[Valletta]], [[Malta]] | completion_date = March 1857 | architect = [[Giuseppe Bonavia]] }}
'''La Borsa''', also known as the '''Exchange Buildings''', is a 19th-century building in [[Valletta]], [[Malta]], which houses '' The Malta Chamber of Commerce, Enterprise and Industry''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historical Context|url=http://www.maltachamber.org.mt/content.aspx?id=189384|website=The Malta Chamber of Commerce, Enterprise and Industry|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414032916/http://www.maltachamber.org.mt/content.aspx?id=189384|archivedate=14 April 2015}}</ref>
The site of La Borsa was originally occupied by a house which belonged to the Priory of Castile. In 1853, the house was handed over to The Malta Chamber of Commerce and Enterprise, which had been formed in 1848. It was demolished to make way for new premises which were designed by the Maltese architect [[Giuseppe Bonavia]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bugeja|first1=Lino|title=Valletta – vibrant city of many styles|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150104/business-news/Valletta-vibrant-city-of-many-styles.550626|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=4 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702024046/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150104/business-news/Valletta-vibrant-city-of-many-styles.550626|archivedate=2 July 2015}}</ref> Works were undertaken by the contractor Michelangelo Azzopardi, and the building was inaugurated in March 1857.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Denaro |first1=Victor F. |title=Houses in Kingsway and Old Bakery Street, Valletta |journal=Melita Historica |date=1959 |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=206-207 |url=http://mhs.eu.pn/mh/19591.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117014317/http://mhs.eu.pn/mh/19591.html |archivedate=2015-11-17 |df= }}</ref> Some features within the building include the Lewis Farrugia Courtyard, Sir Agostino Portelli Hall, the Aula Conciliaris (Council Room), the Banif Lecture Hall and the [[Bank of Valletta|BOV]] Meeting Room.<ref>{{cite web|title=Facilities|url=http://www.maltachamber.org.mt/content.aspx?id=192264|website=The Malta Chamber of Commerce, Enterprise and Industry|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414092203/http://www.maltachamber.org.mt/content.aspx?id=192264|archivedate=14 April 2015}}</ref>
It is scheduled as a Grade 1 national monument by the [[Malta Environment and Planning Authority]].<ref name=oneworld>{{cite news|title=One World: Protecting the most significant buildings, monuments and features of Valletta (16)|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20080626/opinion/one-world.214168|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=26 June 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010151910/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20080626/opinion/one-world.214168|archivedate=10 October 2015}}</ref>
==Architecture== La Borsa was designed by [[Giuseppe Bonavia]] in the [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] architectural style.<ref>[https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=HbCzLhVYkBsC&pg=PA110 p.110]</ref>Its design contrasts with Valletta's traditional architecture. Its façade has an imposing symmetrical [[colonnade]] in the [[Ionic order]]. It has three floors above street level and an underground level. Inaugurated in 1848, the building's design is rather simple but elegant at the same time.<ref name=oneworld/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2014-02-18/books/Commerce-and-Art-working-hand-in-hand-3994812416|title=Commerce and Art working hand in hand - The Malta Independent|website=Independent.com.mt|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref>Felice, David (2013) in Bonello, Giovanni (ed.). ''[https://maltaonlinebookshop.com/product/la-borsa-the-people-the-building-the-history/ La Borsa – The People, The Building, The History]''. p. 45. {{ISBN|9789995733759}}.</ref>
